from Latin <i>rapina</i>), used as a nickname for a rapacious person or a thief.","alternatively, a variant of   Rabin   2, a topographic name denoting residence on ravined terrain, ultimately of the same etymology as 1 above."]},{"name":"Raba","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Manfred.","Polish: status name from <i>rab</i> ‘servant; slave’, or an altered form of German   Rabe  . Compare Hungarian and Czech name   Rab  .","Czech: variant of   Rab   or a nickname from the dialect <i>rabit se</i> ‘to get excited’."]},{"name":"Raben","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hymen.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name containing the element <i>hraban</i> ‘raven’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Rabin  ."]},{"name":"Rabine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Reinhardt.","Jewish: variant of   Rabin  .","Americanized form of German   Rehbein  ."]}]},{"name":"Bertram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. Ravens were traditional symbols of wisdom in Germanic mythology; Odin was regularly accompanied by ravens called Hugin and Munin. This name was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain.  See also  Bertrand ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":85,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionL